        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " is inconceivable. But the truth is, it was peculiarly in keeping with the thoughtful manner of Jesus, if, when a sign ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "from heaven",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " was demanded, He should refer those demanding it to their own practice of interpreting the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "appearances of the sky",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", so as to let them see how blinded they were to the signs that already ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "existed",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". A similar saying is found in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Luke 12:54",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " f., where, however, it is addressed to the multitude. There is no reason for thinking that it appears in its authentic form ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "only",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in Matthew (de Wette), or ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "only",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " in Luke (Schleiermacher, Holtzmann), for there is nothing to prevent us from supposing that Jesus may have used similar and in itself very natural language on several occasions.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ΚΑῚ ΚΑΤΑΛΙΠ. ΑὐΤ. ἈΠῆΛΘΕ",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "span",
            "class": "bld",
            "text": "ΚΑῚ ΚΑΤΑΛΙΠ. ΑὐΤ. ἈΠῆΛΘΕ",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] depicting in a simple way the “justa severitas” (Bengel) shown toward those incorrigibles. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 21:17",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "Comp., besides, the note on ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 12:39",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
